iStock Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories New York - The UN envoy for Libya says 2017 must be "a year of decisions" for the politically fractured North African nation &mdash; first and foremost to get parliament's approval of the national unity government and form a strong army and national police force.Martin Kobler told the UN Security Council on Wednesday that decisions also have to be made on how best to use revenue from Libya's oil production, which has increased to over 700 000 barrels a day, as well as gas exports to end the country's "dire humanitarian situation" and help all Libyans.Chaos has plagued Libya since the ouster and killing of longtime strongman Muammar Gaddafi in a 2011 uprising. The country remains divided between east and west, with no effective government and rival factions and militias.24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.